    <title type="html"><![CDATA[I have a Dream]]></title>
    <link href="http://harshulj.github.com/blog/blog/2012/09/19/i-have-a-dream/"/>
    <updated>2012-09-19T15:10:00+05:30</updated>
    <id>http://harshulj.github.com/blog/blog/2012/09/19/i-have-a-dream</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Martin Luther King, Jr, needs no introduction. I am sure that every one must have heard of him in one context or other.
But most of the people have forgotten what he said. I happen to listen to his famous speech <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Have_a_Dream"><strong>&#8220;I Have a Dream&#8221;</strong></a>.
He talked about equality, freedom and justice. But what amazed me the most was that this phrase was not even there in his origional speech.
His origional speech was titled <span class="highlight"><strong>&#8220;Normalcy, Never Again.&#8221;</strong></span>.</p>

<br> 


<p>But towards the end of the speech black American singer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahalia_Jackson"><strong>Mahalia Jackson</strong></a> shouted to Dr. King from the crowd, <span class="said-text">&#8220;Tell them about the dream, Martin.&#8221;</span>.
And he deviated from his origional speech. He started preaching, punctuating his points with <strong>&#8220;I Have a Dream.&#8221;</strong>. And this speech went on to become the Top American Speech of the 20th century.
This immediately reminded me of his famous saying:</p>

<br>


<blockquote><p>&#8220;Take the first step in faith. You donâ€™t have to see the whole staircase, just take the first step.&#8221;<br/>
<cite> &#8211; Martin Luther King, Jr</cite></p></blockquote>

<br>


<p>This made me wonder how correct his lines were. This will always inspire me. What ever the task may be just get on with it. Don&#8217;t worry whether you will fail or pass, start the task.<br></p>

<br>


<p>Another quote from Dr King. This one will break our heart.</p>

<blockquote><p>In the End, we will remember not the words of our enemies, but the silence of our friends.<br/>
<cite> &#8211; Martin Luther King, Jr</cite></p></blockquote>

<br>

